Duck Typing is a concept in programming that refers to the idea of checking if an object has methods that are expected to be present in an object of a certain type, without necessarily checking if the object actually implements those methods. In other words, it is a way of checking if an object "looks like" an object of a certain type, rather than checking if it is an exact match.

In TypeScript, Duck Typing can be achieved through the use of the `in` operator, which checks if a property or method is present in an object. Here is an example:
```
interface Person {
  name: string;
  sayHello(): void;
}

function isPerson(obj: any): obj is Person {
  return (
    'name' in obj &&
    'sayHello' in obj
  );
}

const person = { name: 'John', sayHello: () => console.log('Hello!') };

if (isPerson(person)) {
  person.sayHello(); // Outputs "Hello!"
}
```
In this example, the `isPerson` function checks if an object `obj` has the properties `name` and `sayHello`. If the object has both of these properties, it returns `true`, indicating that it is an instance of the `Person` interface. The `person` object in this example is an instance of the `Person` interface, so the `isPerson` function returns `true`, and the `sayHello` method can be called on it without any errors.

Duck Typing can be useful in situations where you want to check if an object has certain methods or properties without necessarily checking if it is an exact match. It can also help you catch errors early and improve code maintainability. However, it is important to use Duck Typing judiciously and only when it makes sense for your specific use case. In some cases, it may be better to use a more rigorous type system to ensure that your code is more robust and reliable.

